cal in the study of law today. Legal Canons brings together fifteen essays which seek to map out the legal canon and the way in which law is taught today. In order to understand how the twin ideas of canons and canonicity operate in law, each essay focuses on a particular aspect, from contracts and constitutional law to questions of race and gender. The ascendance of law and economics, feminism, critical race theory, and gay legal studies, as well as the increasing influence of both rational-actor methodology and postmodernism, are all scrutinized by the leading scholars in the field. A timely and comprehensive volume, Legal Canons articulates the need for, and means to, opening the debate on canonicity in legal studies. Table of Contents  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aLawxStudy and teachingzUnited States. 0aLawzUnited StatesvSources. 7aLAW / Government / General.2bisacsh1 aAnsley, Fran, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAyres, Ian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBalkin, J. M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBalkin, Jack, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBartlett, Katharine T., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBobbitt, Philip, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarrington, Paul D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChamallas, Martha, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFarber, Daniel A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFranke, Katherine M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKennedy, Randall, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLevinson, Sanfo